### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

Given the following simplified component:
```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    <h1>dynamic count that works : {{ list().length }}!</h1>
    <h2>computed doesn't update : [{{count()}}]</h2>
    <h2>effect does update : [{{countProp.length}}]</h2>
    <button (click)="add()">add</button>
  `,
})
export class App {
  list = signal<string[]>(['a', 'b'], {
    equal: (arr1: string[], arr2: string[]) => arr1.length === arr2.length,
  });
  count = computed(() => this.list().length);
  countProp: string[] = [];

  constructor() {
    effect(() => (this.countProp = this.list()));
  }

  add() {
    this.list.update((list) => {
      list.push('a');
      return list;
    });
    // it always works if a new array is created
    // this.list.update((list) => [...list, 'a']);
  }
}
```
The signal `count` is not recalculated even though the signal `list` is updated (due to the custom equality function it even emits if an item is added to the array). This is shown with the property `countProb` which is updated in the `effect()` (you can also add a `console.log()` inside `computed()` and `effect()` to see the issue on the console).

If a new array is created (instead to update the existing) the computed signal `count` is updated. As such, I assume the `computed()` function somehow still uses a "short-circuit" equality check which was (partially?) removed in  #53446.

**Please note that in my real use-case I don't have an array within the signal, but a `Map`**



