### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

I've been converting my project to mostly use the new control flow template syntax and I'm really loving it. However, I find myself wanting to add comments to explain logic, and my only option is to use html comment syntax which winds up in the final rendered page, and I'd really love an option to have a comment syntax that does not show up in the rendered page, and it seems easy to add using the new `@` syntax.

### Proposed solution

I think just using `@//` makes a lot of sense

```
@// this is my comment explaining why this logic is here
@if (some complex logic) {
  <div>Some content</div>
} @else {
  <div>Some other content</div>
}
```

### Alternatives considered

I think `//` is the best, most obvious solution, but if `@//` causes parsing issues it could be `@comment` or similar.

Adds support for model inputs in the framework. `model()` returns a writable signal that implicitly defines a input/output pair that can be used either in two-way bindings to keep two values in sync or by binding individually to the input and output. When the value of the `model` changes, it will emit an event with the current value.

Furthermore, these changes expand two-way bindings to accept `WritableSignal`. This will make it easier to transition existing code to signals in a backwards-compatible way.

Example:

```ts
@Directive({
  selector: 'counter',
  standalone: true,
  host: {
    '(click)': 'increment()',
  }
})
export class Counter {
  value = model(0);

  increment(): void {
    this.value.update(current => current + 1);
  }
}

@Component({
  template: `<counter [(value)]="count"/> The current count is: {{count()}}`,
})
class App {
  count = signal(0);
}
```

**Note:** with these changes model inputs should be mostly working. There are a few places where things will be improved in a follow-up PR:
- Ensuring that the language service works correctly with the new TCB for two-way bindings.
- Avoid having to return an object literal from `ModelSignal.subscribe`.
- Figure out the performance implications of checking if the value is a signal each time the `twoWayProperty` instruction is called.
- Figure out if we should remove `applyValueToInputSignal` from `MODEL_SIGNAL_NODE`.
- Avoid the extra variable in the two-way binding TCB.
- Adding a diagnostic when `input()` is mixed with `@Output()` in a two-way binding.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

common

### Description

Sometime there is a need to use a component method into component template. Angular best practice says do not use method into html temlate, eg. `{{ myMethod(2) }}`. With a `GenericPipe` you can use all your public component methods as pure pipe with the component scope (`this`), eg: `{{ 2 | generic: myMethod }}`.

### Proposed solution

see https://github.com/angular/angular/pull/54242

Demo usage:

```ts
import { Component, GenericPipe } from '@angular/core';

interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [GenericPipe, FormsModule],
  template: `
  <input type="search" [(ngModel)]="searchTerm" placeholder="Enter name" >
  <ul>
    <li *ngFor="let user of users | generic: search:searchTerm">{{user.name}}</li>
  </ul>
  `,
})
export class AppComponent {
  users: User[] = [
    { name: 'foo', age: 20 },
    { name: 'bar', age: 20 },
    { name: 'baz', age: 20 },
  ];

  searchTerm = '';

  search(users: User[], searchTerm: string): User[] {
    if (!users || !searchTerm) {
      return users;
    }
    return users.filter(
      (user) => user.name.toLowerCase().indexOf(searchTerm.toLowerCase()) !== -1
    );
  }
}
```

I have also published as NPM library https://www.npmjs.com/package/ng-generic-pipe

